high_level_trends: Bench management repeatedly influenced outcomes: multiple teams left 20+ point performers on the bench across Weeks 1–2 (examples include Caleb Williams, Justin Herbert, J.J. McCarthy, Keon Coleman, Zay Flowers, Jared Goff, Rome Odunze, Daniel Jones).

Quarterback variance has been a major driver of week-to-week swings — several QBs produced huge positive deviations (Josh Allen +17.93 Week 1; Justin Fields +14.03 Week 1 as bench scoring; Jared Goff +18.64 Week 2 on the bench) while other QBs underperformed versus projection (Bo Nix, Joe Burrow, Dak Prescott in Week 1, Josh Allen in Week 2).

Week 1 featured multiple close games decided by single bench/lineup choices (several margins <10). Week 2 produced more lopsided results (several large blowouts), indicating rising disparity between teams that managed lineups/bench optimally and those that did not.
Kickers and defenses produced occasional outlier scoring that swung matchups (Brandon Aubrey 22.0 Week 2; Patriots D/ST 12.0 Week 2; Chargers D/ST 14.0 Week 2).

Clever Team Name Incoming.scoring_pattern: Wins built off a mix of large RB and WR single-game performances and occasional defensive scoring. RB production (Derrick Henry) has been volatile (big in Week 1, low in Week 2).
players_having_impact: Derrick Henry — Week 1 large outperformance (28.7) decisive for that win; Week 2 was a nonfactor (2.3).
Deebo Samuel / Cooper Kupp — steady WR production contributing to team scoring across both weeks.
Patriots D/ST (Week 2) provided an above-projection boost.
Clever Team Name Incoming.bench_management_notes: Left high-scoring bench options in multiple weeks (Geno Smith Week 1 bench positive in Week 1; Jauan Jennings Week 2 17.4 left inactive).

THE Derbaum.scoring_pattern: Explosive WR-led scoring in Week 2 after a closer Week 1. The team can generate very high ceilings when Amon-Ra St. Brown and Ja'Marr Chase both deliver.
players_having_impact: Amon-Ra St. Brown — Week 2 +21.16 vs projection (34.7).
Ja'Marr Chase — Week 2 +13.03 (29.5).
THE Derbaum.bench_management_notes: Possesses depth that produced (Bhayshul Tuten, Elic Ayomanor); in Week 1 the manager left high-scoring bench options (Keon Coleman, J.J. McCarthy) inactive but still won; leveraged starting WR explosions in Week 2.

Puka Puka.scoring_pattern: Wins even in lower total games; Puka Nacua is a consistent receiving anchor. Defense/kicker spikes (Chargers D/ST Week 2) helped one of the victories.
players_having_impact: Puka Nacua — consistent two-week production (18.1, 23.6).
Dak Prescott — volatile (poor Week 1, strong Week 2) but Week 2 QB play helped secure the second win.
Puka Puka.bench_management_notes: Left Zay Flowers (24.6) on the bench in Week 1 — notable unused scoring despite winning.

No Punt Intended.scoring_pattern: Highest points-for in the league through two weeks — offense capable of extremely high outputs, often driven by TE/WR breakouts and bench contributions.
players_having_impact: Javonte Williams — big Week 2 (22.0).
Tucker Kraft — Week 2 breakout (21.4).
Rome Odunze — huge bench output Week 2 (28.3).
No Punt Intended.bench_management_notes: Left Rome Odunze on the bench in Week 2 despite a 28.3 outing; in Week 1 left Justin Fields and Javonte Williams on the bench (both scored large) and lost that matchup, highlighting recurring bench-decision risk.

OHHHHHHH YEAHHHHH!!!!.scoring_pattern: Often dependent on single large QB or RB explosion (Josh Allen Week 1; Jonathan Taylor Week 2). When the QB flops, other pieces have not consistently compensated.
players_having_impact: Josh Allen — massive Week 1 (38.76) then a substantial drop Week 2 (11.82).
Jonathan Taylor — Week 2 carried much of the scoring (28.5).
OHHHHHHH YEAHHHHH!!!!.bench_management_notes: Left Daniel Jones on the bench in Week 2 while he posted 22.84; that was a missed opportunity that likely affected the result.

I Know Exactly What I’m Doing.scoring_pattern: Win achieved via non-traditional scoring sources (kicker and defense spikes) rather than consistent RB/WR production. RBs have been volatile.
players_having_impact: Brandon Aubrey (K) — Week 2 huge kicker score (22.0) materially influenced the matchup.
Juwan Johnson (TE) and Cardinals D/ST — provided surprising upside in Week 2.
I Know Exactly What I’m Doing.bench_management_notes: Left Caleb Williams (24.2 Week 1) on the bench in Week 1; repeated instances of leaving high-upside bench options inactive were observed.

D.J. Chark Week.scoring_pattern: QB-centric floor (Patrick Mahomes produced solid numbers in both weeks) and opportunistic RB/FLEX contributions (Kenneth Walker III).
players_having_impact: Patrick Mahomes — reliable two-week floor (26.02 Week 1, 22.08 Week 2).
Kenneth Walker III — Week 2 flex boost (18.3).
D.J. Chark Week.bench_management_notes: Bench depth produced (George Pickens, Nick Chubb) and provided extra scoring when needed; in Week 1 there was unused positive bench production (J.J. McCarthy was a bench positive week 1 for THE Derbaum, not this team).

Gronk for my johnson.bench_management_notes: Left Justin Herbert (27.92 in Week 1; 18.78 Week 2) on the bench on at least one occasion — a large unused scoring opportunity.

Baker's Brownie Stand.scoring_pattern: Capable of mid-range outputs from QB/WR tandem (Baker Mayfield, Garrett Wilson) but inconsistent RB outputs and special teams/kicker variance hurt totals.

Here Comes McBride.bench_management_notes: Bench players produced (Jameson Williams 17.8 Week 2) but negative D/ST outcomes and some large projection misses cost the team in both weeks.

Goff And Running.bench_management_notes: Left Jared Goff (33.96 Week 2) and Drake Maye (26.3 Week 2) on the bench — the largest single-game bench delta in a matchup and a recurring cause of losses.

players_having_impact: Davante Adams — one of the consistent positives (19.6 Week 2), but insufficient overall.
Chuba Hubbard — contributed but team still low output.
World of Hurts.bench_management_notes: Bench QB Jordan Love produced positively in Week 2 (20.88) but was not always used in starting lineup to rescue below-par outputs.

bench_booms_to_watch.trend: 28.3 as a bench player in Week 2 — illustrative of bench decisions creating swing outcomes.
33.96 bench output in Week 2 — largest single matchup bench delta noted in provided summaries.

recurring_behaviors: Repeated benching of high-upside players: Multiple owners left 20+ point performers inactive across different weeks — a major recurring pattern (examples: Jared Goff left on bench by Goff And Running Week 2; Rome Odunze left on bench by No Punt Intended Week 2; Caleb Williams left on bench by I Know Exactly Week 1).

Willingness to start low-projection kickers/defenses produced outsized returns for some owners: I Know Exactly’s Brandon Aubrey and Puka Puka’s Chargers D/ST both produced far above projections in Week 2 and changed matchup outcomes.

Some owners appear to prioritize upside bench depth but fail to update starting lineups to capture that production; others consistently start speculative plays (TE/defense/kicker) that paid off in single weeks.

summary: Bench attention should remain the primary watchpoint — multiple managers have already lost or narrowly won because of bench decisions.
QB volatility implies weekly outcomes will continue to swing widely; managers who adjust QB choices or exploit favorable matchups will gain advantage.
Kicker and D/ST spikes have been decisive in at least one matchup; they remain low-probability/high-impact assets and should be monitored.
data_driven_flags: Three teams are undefeated (THE Derbaum, Clever Team  Name Incoming, Puka Puka) and currently hold playoff slots; however, their point differentials and bench depth will determine sustainability.

Three teams remain without wins (Here Comes McBride, Goff And Running, World of Hurts) and have exhibited either low points-for or repeated lineup mismanagement — both are risk factors for missing the playoffs.
